The 'History of Photorealism in Comics' section deals with the rivalry between Alex Raymond and Stan Drake which begins to heat up in 1953-54. Cover by Eisner Hall of Fame 2009 inductee, Russ Heath.

In this volume collecting the 6-issue miniseries, an archery contest beckons Oliver Queen's bow-bending son Connor Hawke to the far end of the globe. Accompanied by his old pal Eddie Fyers, Connor accepts the invitation. But a much darker game is afoot, and Connor's life will never be the same!

Starring the Astonishing X-Men and the New Avengers! You know how sometimes you hear the phrase: AND NOTHING WILL EVER BE THE SAME AGAIN? Well, this time believe it, buster! description: The final showdown between the living and the undead! When Hugo Pecos and the FVZA discover the plans of the European vampire council to infect the United States, they quickly locate the underground headquarters of the vampires in the city. As Landra and Vidal split into two squads to thwart the sinister plot of the undead, they realize that there is far more to their mission than simply extermination. A stunning revelation, a tragic death and a shocking betrayal await Landra as she journeys into the belly of the beast to battle the bloodthirsty and ruthless Chaucer and the queen vampire herself - Yaelis.

description: The A-Team have fallen into their deep undercover personas at a very high-profile wedding for an important U.S. official's daughter, seeking to stop a potential terrorist plot before it happens. But, with Murdock cooking, Face event planning, B.A. chauffeuring, and "Reverend" Hannibal presiding, will the wedding be able to survive the A-Team?

With Deep Space Nine descending into chaos, Captain Sisko turns to an unexpected source for assistance-but how can the Cardassian tailor Garak help? It all comes together in this final issue of IDW's debut DEEP SPACE NINE miniseries!

volume.name: Star Trek: Deep Space Nine: Fool's Gold

description: Trapped inside a maximum-security prison, surrounded by DECEPTICONS, and outgunned at every turn, it's time for the newest WRECKERS to earn their stripes. But as the horrors of Garrus-9 are laid bare and the fate of FORTRESS MAXIMUS is revealed, SPRINGER realizes his team has bitten off more than it can chew.

volume.name: The Transformers: Last Stand Of The Wreckers

description: 84's ambassadorship to planet Argos, home of Earth's champion, Atlas, has taken a very strange turn: She's been made the leader of their armed forces and sent into battle against an ancient enemy! Meanwhile, the junior Emerald Gauntlet, Kevin, with his newly augmented powers, is being sent to claim a most powerful artifact from being taken by a race the Emerald Ones consider to be the greatest evil they know. But why is Alexandra Von Fogg so willing to work with the Emerald Ones to enhance Kevin, the son of her family's greatest foe?

Neuermann Giesel is the cat's meow of Ubelandia's 20-something party scene. So it's only natural that BSAA Agents Gere and Sugarman wonder why he's chosen to hang at the remote jungle compound of Fritz Giesel the CEO of Giesel Industries instead of at a trendy club. And a tour of the compound turns deadly as the two agents are caught in Neuermann's idea of a T-Virus play date.
name: Ich Bin Ein Schlechtes Genie...

description: Uneasy graverobbers One-Eye and Pointyface return from looting the mountains to Skrubtown, an orc gang stronghold. There, they must pay tribute to the local boss, 'The Norman', or face his blood soaked chopping block.
name: II: The Chopping Block

description: Dayglo & Martin give us a completely new take on TANK GIRL-grittier, bloodier, and weirder than ever before. 'The Royal Escape' finds Tank Girl and her team stranded on the outskirts of a city they have just destroyed, as an immense and vengeful army approaches. Not recommended for children, the elderly, or wussies.
name: The Golden Egg

description:
Joe and Pete set up a stakeout across from a ninja school and a restaurant filled with demonic cannibals. There may not be enough turtle soda and old cop movies to prepare them for the fight ahead...

Dont miss the next chapter of Brandon Grahams saga of weird!

It's the thrilling next chapter of BRANDON GRAHAM's saga!

The coffin is open and the thing inside it walks among us!

Statues cry, rivers turn black! In short, s@!# is going down!

This is the issue not to miss, as Joe opens up a can of feline whup-ass!

Deacon Frost has taken over New Orleans Mafiaand Marie Laveau is his wing woman in evil! Draculas reign as Lord of Vampires takes a dangerous turn- one that involves the capture of Blade, Hannibal King, and Brother Voodoo!

Blade sits in his New York home, contemplating his status as last surviving member of Quincy Harker's vampire hunters. He also ponders a recent spate of killings, the victims being underground criminal figures. His current activity slaying the undead brings a trio of bloodsuckers to invade his abode. Blade kills two of them, then tortures the third till he extracts the name of the mastermind behind the mob murders: Deacon Frost, who has taken over a crime family in New Orleans. Blade finishes off the vampire, then packs and leaves for Louisiana.

In New Orleans, as he searches for Frost, Blade recalls his previous encounters with the vampire, especially the death of his mother at Frost's hands, occurring at the time of his birth. A meeting with Brother Voodoo at a night club proves fruitless beyond being informed that Marie Laveau, the Voodoo Queen, is active again. On the street, Blade is attacked by, then dispatches, three vampires, as Hannibal King makes his presence known. King tells Blade he survived the explosion that appeared to have destroyed him and that he's been hired by Safron Caulder, Blade's former lover, to trail Frost. The vampire has been making moves to take over Donna Garth's coffee manufacturing company, where Safron works. The next day, Blade visits Safron and Donna to ask what they know. He learns that Frost's takeover of one criminal organization has ignited a mob war.

That evening, Laveau performs a ritual to create zuvembies, but is interrupted by Brother Voodoo. However, the Voodoo Queen has recently allied herself with Frost's vampires and several of the creatures attack and subdue him.

Elsewhere, Blade and King case the streets where they witness vampires killing rival mob enforcers. The gunmen proved to be bait, as human gangsters come out of hiding to attack the bloodsuckers, but then more vampires join the fray which erupts into a gruesome battle. Waiting till the chaos subsides, Blade and King follow some surviving vampires to their hideout, an old paddleboat. As the pair try to board, they are ambushed and captured.

Soon, they are nailed to a wall by their hands beside the similarly incapacitated Brother Voodoo, King enmeshed in a net laced with garlic. Deacon Frost presides over the scene, boasting of his plan to become the new lord of vampires, a plan which is proceeding apace as he takes over gangs and big businesses. He claims that, as the city's crime boss, New Orleans is under his control, and soon other cities will fall to him in the same way. He then leaves to make his final play against Donna Garth and her company.

Blade manages to move his pinned hand enough to extract a knife from his sleeve, passing it to King, who painstakingly cuts through his net. Now able to transform to mist, King frees his allies, and Brother Voodoo faces off against Laveau. Invoking Damballah's aid, he defeats the priestess, but the resultant mystic energies cause an explosion which kills the remaining vampires as trio jump overboard.

At Garth Manor, Donna and Safron are threatened by Frost, who demands Donna sign her company over to him. Soon, Blade and King arrive, and while the detective deals with the vampire guards outside, Blade bursts in to face Frost. The fight goes badly for Blade at first, as the vampire throws him around like a rag doll. But when Donna and Safron distract Frost, Blade flings a wooden knife into his throat, then hacks off one of his arms. Frost leaps out a window and vanishes.

The next morning, Blade and King discuss their next moves; King is being retained by Donna who wants him to find the missing Zombie that was once her father, and Blade says he's decided to take up residence in New Orleans to continue his campaign against Frost.

Comicdom's leading Pre-Code horror reprint anthology is back, bigger and better than ever- it's AC Comic's Crypt of Horror, Volume 8!! Inside the classic Warren Kremer cover, you'll find 140 pages of 1950's terror tales from defunct publishers like Magazine Enterprises, Standard/Nedor, Hillman, ACG, Comic Media, Mikeross, Harvey, Fiction House and others, guaranteed to chill your spine. Featuring timeless tales like"The Witch of the Haunted Hills", "Saleman of Death", "Ghostly Revenge"; "Here's To Horror"; "The Hungry Horde";"Web For Her Wedding Dress", "Creamation"; "Hidden Graveyard"; "Curse of the Zamboori"; "The Crown of Coort"; "Kiss and Kill"; "Clumsy"; "the Gost of Dr. Renick"; "Rotting Flesh of the Dead"; "Visitor"; "The Lucky Stiff"; "Nightmare Island" and more- many of them introduced by own happy horror host, LON MADNIGHT himself!! Thrill to the artwork of such line-art luminaries as: Sheldon Moldoff, Jerry Grandenetti, Dick Ayers, Bob Powell, Bill Benulis, Paul Hodge, Howard Nostrand, Gene Fawcette, Rocke Mastroserio, Bill Fraccio, Bob Forgione, Bill Ely and others, in some of the WEIRDEST macabre fantasy tales you've ever read- all in perfect, sparkling, crystal-clear reproduction on full , complete stories, exactly as they appeared back in "the good old days" of horror comics. We didn't get up to Volume 8 in this series because vintage horror fans DON'T love this book- it's a great value and hours of comic-reading entertainment. Standard comic-book size, 140 pages, black and white interiors with full-color covers, saddle-stitched. Printed in 2010.
name: Volume 8

Batwoman must stop Alice from unleashing a toxic death cloud over all of Gotham City - but Alice has more up her sleeve than just poison, and Batwoman's life will never be the same.

The 7-issue miniseries event that rocked the entire DC Universe in 2005-2006 - a sequal to the epic CRISIS ON INFINITE EARTHS - is now collected in an amazing hardcover collection! Written by Geoff Johns (GREEN LANTERN, TEEN TITANS) with art by a who's who of comics' greatest talents - including Phil Jiminez, George Perez, Jerry Ordway, and more, this hardcover is a must have for any DC collector.

OMAC robots are rampaging, magic is dying, villains are uniting, and a war is raging in space. And in the middle of it all, a critical moment has divided Earth's three greatest heroes: Superman, Batman, and Wonder Woman. It's the DCU's darkest day, and long-lost heroes from the past have returned to make things right in the universe...at any cost. Heroes will live, heroes will die, and the DCU will never be the same again!

This exhaustive volume also contains every cover and variant produced for the project, annotations, character designs, excerpts from scripts, unused scenes, and much more.
name: Infinite Crisis

description: From humble beginnings in Chicago, she rose to become an outspoken advocate, trailblazing First Lady, and international style icon. So how has she adjusted to life in the White House? Relive the exciting, eventful, history making first year of First Lady Michelle Obama. From traveling the globe to barnstorming the nation in support of her husband's policies, it's been an unpredictable 12 months worthy of its own full-length, full-color comic book chronicle.

volume.name: Female Force: Michelle Obama: Year One

description: Dash learns the real secret behind the Underminer's attacks on Metroville--and what he finds out may pit him against his own family! More Incredibles action from comics legend Mark Waid and Landry Walker in this new ongoing series!

It's The Agency vs The Organization in a battle of spy vs spy. Unfortunately for Donald Duck, his alter ego, Double Duck, is caught smack in the middle of the action. Will the world's number one undercover duck be able to foil the Organization's evil plans and still be home in time for dinner? Find out this month in another exciting installment of Double Duck!

Lightning McQueens new Radiator Springs Racetrack is finally finished, and the crowds are descending on the town for the inaugural event but his rival Chick Hicks has some plans to make sure McQueen loses the first big race on his own turf in this new ongoing series!

The war with the Red Blade comes to a dramatic, spectacular finish, as our desperate heroes pull out all the stops to keep the alien invaders from eradicating all life on Earth! Who, if anyone, will be left standing, and what kind of planet will be left for them to try to rebuild?

The sole survivor of all that was Asgard, will Beta Ray Bill escape the end of one world only to face his own end in the form of an enemy greater than any he has battled before? Introducing Stardust, a creature of cosmic power who turns his enemies to dust to fuel the stars. And that's just what he intends to do to Beta Ray Bill, and the Korbinite people, but he's only following orders. The question is: from whom? The answer is big, and we mean BIG!

Reprints Stormbreaker: The Saga of Beta Ray Bill #1-6.

Your street-level view of the Hulk's invasion! The Green Goliath has returned to Earth on a collision course with some of Marvel's mightiest heroes. So what does that mean for the ordinary people caught in the crossfire? Ben Urich and Sally Floyd, fresh from their appearance in Civil War: Front Line, pound the pavement to uncover the story behind the story! Plus: Who wants our tireless reporters to take down J. Jonah Jameson, and how do they want them to do it? Grab your press pass, and join the Civil War: Front Line team of writer Paul Jenkins and artist Ramon Bachs as they take you to the middle of the action. Also featuring the Prologue to World War Hulk! As Hulk's great stone ship approaches the planet, he prepares for the war on the horizon by reliving past conflicts with Iron Man, the Fantastic Four, Doctor Strange and the Inhumans.

description: Jubilee is interrogated by the sinister Agent Gyrich, while the X-Men's raid on Mutant Registration Agency meets unexpected resistance as the Sentinels arrive. In a tough battle the X-Men have to leave two of their own behind - Morph and Beast. Wolverine swears revenge.

Cable attacks the Leader and Cameron Hodge on Genosha, ready to bring them to justice. Their standstill is broken when Storm destroys the dam, seemingly ruining Master Mold and his Sentinels in process. Storm, Jubilee and Gambit are then reunited with the other X-Men, while the Blob, Mystique and Pyro decide that they have "nothing to do here". On return to Salem Center the X-Men discover that Xavier's mansion has been destroyed, and Professor X himself is nowhere to be found. They find a message from Xavier, stating that he had to leave immediately. While looking for the attacker Jubilee and Wolverine encounter Colossus, who's soon arrested under false accusation. Rogue, charmed by Colossus's muscles and personality, suggests they help him get his freedom back.

Rogue and Storm break Colossus out of prison. Meanwhile, Jubilee and Wolverine find the Juggernaut - the man who had really attacked Xavier's School. After a short fight Juggernaut clearly has the upper hand, but then the other X-Men and Colossus join in. Working as a team, they're able to remove the Juggernaut's helmet, making him vulnerable to Jean Grey's telepathy. After the brainwashed Juggernaut wanders off, the X-Men work on rebuilding the school, wondering about the Professor's fate. This issue included a page with the brief description of Xavier and his students, including Morph but without Jubilee.

Warren Worthington is attacked by Cable, who's looking for Dr Adler. On Muir Island, Professor X tries to find out what is Dr Adler really doing in his very private, very secretive laboratory, but even his telepathy doesn't help much. When the X-Men learn that Adler supposedly knows how to "cure" mutations, Rogue flies to Muir Island, where she has a pleasant conversation with Pyro and Avalanche and remembers her fateful first kiss with Cody. Adler, who's really Mystique in disguise, is ordered by Apocalypse to transform Rogue into one of his followers.

Pyro and Avalanche kidnap Dr Adler, since everyone seems to be interested in him. They're surprised to find out that it's actually Mystique, and that the real Adler was apparently destroyed by Apocalypse. Rogue, Cable, and Cyclops and Jean Grey all arrive and participate in a struggle for "Adler"'s life. During the fight Cable falls down from a cliff, seemingly to his doom. Jean Grey falls, too, but is saved by Rogue, who decides that she needs her powers, even if they make her alienated. Warren Worthington arrives and asks "Adler" for help. Apocalypse orders Mystique to transform Warren into his slave, and claims that he will destroy the world.

Several mutants gather on Muir Island, looking for a cure for their uncontrollable powers. The appearance of seemingly cured Warren Worthington is all that they need to accept Adler's offer to cure them. Cyclops claims that their powers are a gift, not a disease, but the mutants don't listen. Xavier and the X-Men return to Westchester. Meanwhile, Mystique and Apocalypse transform four mutants into Horsemen of Apocalypse. They attack the world peace summit in Paris. The X-Men see the attack on TV, and Xavier is worried by the threat of Apocalypse. He also recognizes the four Horsemen as the mutants treated by Adler, and sends Rogue back to Muir Island to find out the truth about Adler and his work.

Apocalypse sends his Horsemen to wreak chaos upon the world. Meanwhile, Rogue returns to Muir Island to find out the truth about Dr Adler and his machine. She intimidates Adler - who is actually Mystique - into revealing her true colors, and learns that Apocalypse controls his Horsemen by channeling their anger, and the location of his base beneath the Stonehenge. Picking a moment when Rogue turns her back to her, Mystique shoots Rogue and destroys the machine, leaving no chance of changing the Horsemen back.

The X-Men, lead by Cyclops, counterattack the Horsemen and force them to retreat to Stonehenge. Having followed their enemies, the X-Men find Rogue fighting a losing battle against Apocalypse. During the following fight Rogue touches Archangel and absorbs his anger, making him realize what he has become.

Apocalypse and the three remaining Horsemen escape. Archangel asks Rogue not to give in to the anger that's now inside her, saying that he wasn't strong enough before flying off.

It's 2055, and America is ruled by mutant-hunting Sentinels. Aged Wolverine meets two younger mutants, who are attacked by Sentinel robots, and after that - Bishop, a mutant who works for Sentinels, hunting other mutants. Bishop captures all three and brings them to disposal center, only to find out that he is not needed anymore and will be disposed of, too. Joining forces, Wolverine and Bishop break free and manage to reach Forge's secret laboratory, where a working time machine is located. Forge has a theory that by preventing an assassination in the 1990's, it is possible to change the future. Wolverine plans to go back to the past and kill the assassin, but Bishop takes his place, claiming that he's younger and that the assassin's was one of the X-Men, Wolverine's old friend, so it would be hard for Wolverine to pull the trigger.

After he moves to the past, Bishop can't remember the details of his mission. He only knows that he needs to stop the assassin... and it is one of the X-Men.

Bishop infiltrates Xavier's mansion. Though Jubilee is fooling around instead of watching the monitors, she alerts the X-Men in time to give Bishop a warm welcome. Bishop attacks Cyclops and Storm, doing well against them, but is defeated by Wolverine's sneak attack, which unlocks some of his memories - Bishop remembers that it was Wolverine who sent him back to the past to stop the assassin from killing someone important.

Analyzing Bishop's gun, the X-Men come to the conclusion that it really came from the future. Professor X reads Bishop's mind and is horrified by the dark future where Sentinels destroy all the mutants. The X-Men argue about Bishop and if it's possible to trust him when another time traveller arrives - the ultimate robot hunter, Nimrod. Together the X-Men and Bishop manage to defeat Nimrod and send him back to his time. The arguement starts anew, with Cyclops claiming that whoever the assassin is, it can't be Jean. Wolverine suspects Bishop of foul play, and Jubilee remarks that Wolverine is probably the most suspicious character. The issue ends with Rogue's arrival.

The X-Men deduce that Senator Robert Kelly is the highly probable target, and fly off to Washington to try and prevent the assassination, leaving Wolverine to guard Gambit and Bishop in Xavier's mansion. Gambit is very displeased by this lack of trust, but Jubilee manages to calm him down, and he agrees that he should behave more like an adult.

The unlikely romance between the Vision and the Scarlet Witch was one of the Avengers' most famous storylines. Now, witness what happens when the two heroes finally get hitched and settle down in the suburbs! If you think they're going to live the quiet life, think again! See how a match made in heaven led to a wedding in Limbo, and how a Halloween horror proves that there's still magic in their marriage! Plus: A golden age mystery with ties to the Witch's past is solved! The Vision bonds with his brothers in all but blood -- but who is the Scarlet Witch's father? Marvel's oddest couple shows that home is where the heroes are! Guest-starring the Avengers and the Inhumans vs. Dormammu, the Grim Reaper and more!
